	<LINE>EELIGIOUS AND MOEAL INSTITUTIONS.</LINE>
	<LINE>SCOTTISH PERMISSIVE BILL AND TEM-</LINE>
	<LINE>PEEANCE ASSOCIATION.</LINE>
	<LINE>Object. — The promotion of total abstinence as a</LINE>
	<LINE>rule of life, the creation of an enlightened public</LINE>
	<LINE>opinion in favour of the Suppression of all Traffic in</LINE>
	<LINE>Intoxicating Liquors as leverages, and to secure,</LINE>
	<LINE>through the united efforts of moral and social re-</LINE>
	<LINE>formers, the passage into law of a measure framed to</LINE>
	<LINE>effectually suppress that traffic by the votes of the</LINE>
	<LINE>ratepayers.</LINE>
	<LINE>Treasurer Hamilton, Glasgow, president; vice-</LINE>
	<LINE>presidents, Sir Wilfrid Lawson, Bart., M.P.; James</LINE>
	<LINE>Stewart, M.P. ; Sir J. Murray, Bart., Philiphaugh ;</LINE>
	<LINE>ex-Bailie Moncur, Dundee ; Bailie Jamieson, Perth ;</LINE>
	<LINE>J. D. Bryce, J.P. ; ex-Provost Ferguson, Partick; J.</LINE>
	<LINE>Eoberton, J.P. ; Professor W. G. Blaikie, D.D., Edin-</LINE>
	<LINE>burgh; Professor Kirk, &amp;c., with upwards of 120</LINE>
	<LINE>hon. vice-presidents and directors; James Torrens,</LINE>
	<LINE>J.P., chairman of executive; ex-Provost Dick, vice-</LINE>
	<LINE>chairman of do, ; E. M'Callum, treasurer ; Bailie</LINE>
	<LINE>Selkirk, hon. secy., E. Mackay, secretary, 112 Bath</LINE>
	<LINE>Street. Official organ, " Social Reformer," published</LINE>
	<LINE>monthly, one penny. The income last year amounted</LINE>
	<LINE>to £2074 Is. lid., and the balance to carry forward</LINE>
	<LINE>was £59 2s. The surplus assets amounted to</LINE>
	<LINE>£148 10s. 8id.</LINE>
	<LINE>The number of meetings addressed by representa-</LINE>
	<LINE>tives of the Association in the course of a year ranges</LINE>
	<LINE>from 800 to 1000. The Association fully employs</LINE>
	<LINE>five agents and secretary, besides agents in various</LINE>
	<LINE>parts of the country, who are meantime partially</LINE>
	<LINE>engaged. Scotland is divided into districts, with</LINE>
	<LINE>headquarters in Glasgow, Edinburgh, Aberdeen, and</LINE>
	<LINE>Peebles. The Association has increased its Parlia-</LINE>
	<LINE>mentary position materially. On the 18th of June,</LINE>
	<LINE>1880, the division on the Local Option Resolution of</LINE>
	<LINE>Sir Wilfrid Lawson, Bart., affirming the right of the</LINE>
	<LINE>ratepayers to veto the liquor traffic of their own dis-</LINE>
	<LINE>tricts by the vote of a majority of their number, showed</LINE>
	<LINE>that of the 60 parliamentary representatives for Scot-</LINE>
	<LINE>land 40, or two-thirds of the whole, voted for the</LINE>
	<LINE>resolution, 3 hon. members paired in its favour, and</LINE>
	<LINE>5 only voted for its rejection : thus giving a majority</LINE>
	<LINE>of 8 to 1 in favour of granting enabling powers to</LINE>
	<LINE>ratepayers to abolish all traffic in alcoholic liquors</LINE>
	<LINE>■when they so determine. No other question relating</LINE>
	<LINE>to Scotland can show anything approaching to such</LINE>
	<LINE>a decided expression of opinion as is indicated by</LINE>
	<LINE>these figures. Government, constrained by the adop-</LINE>
	<LINE>tion of Sir Wilfrid Lawson's local option resolution</LINE>
	<LINE>by 245 to 219, has promised through the Premier to</LINE>
	<LINE>embody the principle of that resolution in their forth-</LINE>
	<LINE>coming legislation on the drink traffic. To enable</LINE>
	<LINE>the Association to maintain the agitation for a sup-</LINE>
	<LINE>pressive liquor veto with unabated vigour, and to</LINE>
	<LINE>bring the influence of the Scottish electorate to bear</LINE>
	<LINE>successfully upon the government of the day, liberal</LINE>
	<LINE>subscriptions to the funds are urgently required, and</LINE>
	<LINE>will be gratefully received at the offices or by the</LINE>
	<LINE>agents. Subscribers to the Association of £1 and</LINE>
	<LINE>upwards yearly receive a copy of the Alliance News</LINE>
	<LINE>weekly, and the Social Reformer monthly, free ; while</LINE>
	<LINE>subscribers of 5s. per annum receive the Social Re-</LINE>
	<LINE>■'brmer, post free, as issued. Please note the address</LINE>
	<LINE>—112 Bath Street.</LINE>
